# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: machine-translation-nlp
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] In machine learning, **attention** is a method that determines the importance of each component in a sequence relative to the other components in that sequence.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] In natural language processing, importance is represented by "soft" weights assigned to each word in a sentence.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] More generally, attention encodes vectors called token embeddings across a fixed-width sequence that can range from tens to millions of tokens in size.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] Unlike "hard" weights, which are computed during the backwards training pass, "soft" weights exist only in the forward pass and therefore change with every step of the input.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] Earlier designs implemented the attention mechanism in a serial recurrent neural network (RNN) language translation system, but a more recent design, namely the transformer, removed the slower sequential RNN and relied more heavily on the faster parallel attention scheme.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] Inspired by ideas about attention in humans, the attention mechanism was developed to address the weaknesses of using information from the hidden layers of recurrent neural networks.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] Recurrent neural networks favor information contained in words at the end of a sentence and thus deemed more recent, thereby tending to attenuate the significance and associated predictive weight assigned to information earlier in the sentence.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] Attention allows a token equal access to any part of a sentence directly, rather than only through the previous state.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] Additional surveys of the attention mechanism in deep learning are provided by Niu et al. and Soydaner.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] The major breakthrough came with self-attention, where each element in the input sequence attends to all others, enabling the model to capture global dependencies.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] This idea was central to the Transformer architecture, which replaced recurrence with attention mechanisms.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] As a result, Transformers became the foundation for models like BERT, T5 and generative pre-trained transformers (GPT).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] The modern era of machine attention was revitalized by grafting an attention mechanism (Fig 1. orange) to an Encoder-Decoder.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] Figure 2 shows the internal step-by-step operation of the attention block (A) in Fig 1.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] The diagram shows the attention forward pass calculating correlations of the word "that" with other words in "See that girl run." Given the right weights from training, the network should be able to identify "girl" as a highly correlated word.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] In translating between languages, alignment is the process of matching words from the source sentence to words of the translated sentence.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] Networks that perform verbatim translation without regard to word order would show the highest scores along the (dominant) diagonal of the matrix.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] The off-diagonal dominance shows that the attention mechanism is more nuanced.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] Consider an example of translating *I love you* to French.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] On the first pass through the decoder, 94% of the attention weight is on the first English word *I*, so the network offers the word *je*.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] On the second pass of the decoder, 88% of the attention weight is on the third English word *you*, so it offers *t'*.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] On the last pass, 95% of the attention weight is on the second English word *love*, so it offers *aime*.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] In the *I love you* example, the second word *love* is aligned with the third word *aime*.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] Sometimes, alignment can be multiple-to-multiple.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] For example, the English phrase *look it up* corresponds to *cherchez-le*.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] For convolutional neural networks, attention mechanisms can be distinguished by the dimension on which they operate, namely: spatial attention, channel attention, or combinations.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] These variants recombine the encoder-side inputs to redistribute those effects to each target output.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] Often, a correlation-style matrix of dot products provides the re-weighting coefficients.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] In the figures below, W is the matrix of context attention weights, similar to the formula in Overview section above.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] The size of the attention matrix is proportional to the square of the number of input tokens.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] Therefore, when the input is long, calculating the attention matrix requires a lot of GPU memory.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] Flash attention is an implementation that reduces the memory needs and increases efficiency without sacrificing accuracy.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] It achieves this by partitioning the attention computation into smaller blocks that fit into the GPU's faster on-chip memory, reducing the need to store large intermediate matrices and thus lowering memory usage while increasing computational efficiency.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] FlexAttention is an attention kernel developed by Meta that allows users to modify attention scores prior to softmax and dynamically chooses the optimal attention algorithm.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] Attention is widely used in natural language processing, computer vision, and speech recognition.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] In NLP, it improves context understanding in tasks like question answering and summarization.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] In vision, visual attention helps models focus on relevant image regions, enhancing object detection and image captioning.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] From the original paper on vision transformers (ViT), visualizing attention scores as a heat map (called saliency maps or attention maps) has become an important and routine way to inspect the decision making process of ViT models.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] One can compute the attention maps with respect to any attention head at any layer, while the deeper layers tend to show more semantically meaningful visualization.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] Attention rollout is a recursive algorithm to combine attention scores across all layers, by computing the dot product of successive attention maps.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] Because vision transformers are typically trained in a self-supervised manner, attention maps are generally not class-sensitive.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] When a classification head is attached to the ViT backbone, class-discriminative attention maps (CDAM) combines attention maps and gradients with respect to the class `[CLS]` token.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] Some class-sensitive interpretability methods originally developed for convolutional neural networks can be also applied to ViT, such as GradCAM, which back-propagates the gradients to the outputs of the final attention layer.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] Using attention as basis of explanation for the transformers in language and vision is not without debate.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] While some pioneering papers analyzed and framed attention scores as explanations, higher attention scores do not always correlate with greater impact on model performances.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] The matrix Q contains m queries, while matrices $K,V$ jointly contain an *unordered* set of n key-value pairs.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] Value vectors in matrix V are weighted using the weights resulting from the softmax operation, so that the rows of the m -by- $d_{v}$ output matrix are confined to the convex hull of the points in $\mathbb {R} ^{d_{v}}$ given by the rows of V .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] To understand the permutation invariance and permutation equivariance properties of QKV attention, let $A\in \mathbb {R} ^{m\times m}$ and $B\in \mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ be permutation matrices; and $D\in \mathbb {R} ^{m\times n}$ an arbitrary matrix.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] These properties are inherited when applying linear transforms to the inputs and outputs of QKV attention blocks.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] For example, a simple self-attention function defined as: $X\mapsto {\text{Attention}}(XT_{q},XT_{k},XT_{v})$ is permutation equivariant with respect to re-ordering the rows of the input matrix X in a non-trivial way, because every row of the output is a function of all the rows of the input.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] Similar properties hold for *multi-head attention*, which is defined below.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] The softmax output, also in $\mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ is then *lower triangular*, with zeros in all elements above the diagonal.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] The masking ensures that for all $1\leq i<j\leq n$ , row i of the attention output is independent of row j of any of the three input matrices.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] The permutation invariance and equivariance properties of standard QKV attention do not hold for the masked variant.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] The permutation properties of (standard, unmasked) QKV attention apply here also.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] For permutation matrices, $A,B$ : ${\text{MultiHead}}(AQ,BK,BV)=A\,{\text{MultiHead}}(Q,K,V)$ from which we also see that multi-head self-attention: $X\mapsto {\text{MultiHead}}(XT_{q},XT_{k},XT_{v})$ is equivariant with respect to re-ordering of the rows of input matrix X .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] ${\text{Attention}}(Q,K,V)={\text{softmax}}(QWK^{T})V$ where W is a learnable weight matrix.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] Self-attention is essentially the same as cross-attention, except that query, key, and value vectors all come from the same model.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] Both encoder and decoder can use self-attention, but with subtle differences.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] For encoder self-attention, we can start with a simple encoder without self-attention, such as an "embedding layer", which simply converts each input word into a vector by a fixed lookup table.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] This gives a sequence of hidden vectors $h_{0},h_{1},\dots$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] This can be applied repeatedly, to obtain a multilayered encoder.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] This is the "encoder self-attention", sometimes called the "all-to-all attention", as the vector at every position can attend to every other.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] For decoder self-attention, all-to-all attention is inappropriate, because during the autoregressive decoding process, the decoder cannot attend to future outputs that has yet to be decoded.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] This can be solved by forcing the attention weights $w_{ij}=0$ for all $i<j$ , called "causal masking".
[src:machine-translation-nlp/attention-machine-learning] This attention mechanism is the "causally masked self-attention".
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] In computer science, **beam search** is a heuristic search algorithm that explores a graph by expanding the most promising node in a limited set.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] Beam search is a modification of best-first search that reduces its memory requirements.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] Best-first search is a graph search which orders all partial solutions (states) according to some heuristic.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] But in beam search, only a predetermined number of best partial solutions are kept as candidates.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] Beam search uses breadth-first search to build its search tree.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] At each level of the tree, it generates all successors of the states at the current level, sorting them in increasing order of heuristic cost.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] However, it only stores a predetermined number, $\beta$ , of best states at each level (called the beam width).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] The greater the beam width, the fewer states are pruned.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] With an infinite beam width, no states are pruned and beam search is identical to best-first search.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] Conversely, a beam width of 1 corresponds to a hill-climbing algorithm.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] The beam width bounds the memory required to perform the search.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] Since a goal state could potentially be pruned, beam search sacrifices completeness (the guarantee that an algorithm will terminate with a solution, if one exists).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] Beam search is not optimal (that is, there is no guarantee that it will find the best solution).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] A beam search is most often used to maintain tractability in large systems with insufficient amount of memory to store the entire search tree.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] For example, it has been used in many machine translation systems.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] (The state of the art now primarily uses neural machine translation based methods, especially large language models.) To select the best translation, each part is processed, and many different ways of translating the words appear.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] The top best translations according to their sentence structures are kept, and the rest are discarded.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] The translator then evaluates the translations according to a given criterion, choosing the translation which best keeps the goals.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] The Harpy Speech Recognition System (introduced in a 1976 dissertation) was the first use of what would become known as beam search.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] While the procedure was originally referred to as the "locus model of search", the term "beam search" was already in use by 1977.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] Beam search has been made complete by combining it with depth-first search, resulting in *beam stack search* and *depth-first beam search*, and with limited discrepancy search, resulting in *beam search using limited discrepancy backtracking* (BULB).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] The resulting search algorithms are anytime algorithms that find good but likely sub-optimal solutions quickly, like beam search, then backtrack and continue to find improved solutions until convergence to an optimal solution.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] Since local beam search often ends up on local maxima, a common solution is to choose the next $\beta$ states in a random way, with a probability dependent from the heuristic evaluation of the states.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] This kind of search is called *stochastic beam search*.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/beam-search] Other variants are *flexible beam search* and *recovery beam search*.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In deep learning, the **transformer** is a family of artificial neural network architectures based on the multi-head attention mechanism, in which text is converted to numerical representations called tokens, and each token is converted into a vector via lookup from a word embedding table.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] At each layer, each token is then contextualized within the scope of the context window with other (unmasked) tokens via a parallel multi-head attention mechanism, allowing the signal for key tokens to be amplified and less important tokens to be diminished.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Because self-attention alone is permutation-invariant, transformers inject positional information, typically through positional encodings or learned positional embeddings, so token order can affect the output.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Transformers have the advantage of having no recurrent units, therefore requiring less training time than earlier recurrent neural architectures (RNNs) such as long short-term memory (LSTM).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Later variations have been widely adopted for training large language models (LLMs) on large (language) datasets.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Modern transformer designs are commonly grouped into encoder-only, decoder-only, and encoder-decoder variants, depending on whether they are optimized for representation learning, autoregressive generation, or conditional sequence-to-sequence tasks.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The original version of the transformer architecture was proposed in the 2017 paper "Attention Is All You Need" by researchers at Google.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The predecessors of transformers were developed as an improvement over previous architectures for machine translation, but have found many applications since.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] They are used in large-scale natural language processing, computer vision (vision transformers), reinforcement learning, audio, multimodal learning, robotics, and playing chess.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It has also led to the development of pre-trained systems, such as generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) and BERT (bidirectional encoder representations from transformers).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] For many years, sequence modelling and generation was done by using plain recurrent neural networks (RNNs).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A well-cited early example was the Elman network (1990).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In theory, the information from one token can propagate arbitrarily far down the sequence, but in practice the vanishing-gradient problem leaves the model's state at the end of a long sentence without precise, extractable information about preceding tokens.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A key breakthrough was LSTM (originally described in a 1995 technical report and formally published in 1997), an RNN that introduced gating mechanisms to mitigate the vanishing gradient problem, allowing efficient learning of long-sequence modelling.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] One key architectural element was the use of *multiplicative gating units*, in which the outputs of some neurons modulate the outputs of others.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] These multiplicative units are conceptually distinct from the additive attention mechanism later introduced for sequence-to-sequence models.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Neural networks using multiplicative units were later called *sigma-pi networks* or *higher-order networks*.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] LSTM became the standard architecture for long sequence modelling until the 2017 publication of transformers.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] However, LSTM still used sequential processing, like most other RNNs.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Specifically, RNNs operate one token at a time from first to last; they cannot operate in parallel over all tokens in a sequence.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Modern transformers overcome this problem, but unlike RNNs, they require computation time that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The linearly scaling fast weight controller (1992) learns to compute a weight matrix for further processing depending on the input.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] One of its two networks has "fast weights" or "dynamic links" (1981).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A slow neural network learns by gradient descent to generate keys and values for computing the weight changes of the fast neural network which computes answers to queries.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This was later shown to be equivalent to the unnormalized linear transformer.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The idea of encoder–decoder sequence transduction had been developed in the early 2010s; commonly cited as the originators that produced seq2seq are two concurrently published papers from 2014.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A 380M-parameter model for machine translation uses two long short-term memories (LSTM).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The *encoder* is an LSTM that takes in a sequence of tokens and turns it into a vector.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The *decoder* is another LSTM that converts the vector into a sequence of tokens.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Similarly, another 130M-parameter model used gated recurrent units (GRU) instead of LSTM.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Later research showed that GRUs are neither better nor worse than LSTMs for seq2seq.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] These early seq2seq models had no attention mechanism, and the state vector is accessible only after the *last* word of the source text was processed.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Although in theory such a vector retains the information about the whole original sentence, in practice the information is poorly preserved.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This is because the input is processed sequentially by one recurrent network into a *fixed*-size output vector, which is then processed by another recurrent network into an output.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] If the input is long, then the output vector would not be able to contain all relevant information, degrading the output.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] As evidence, reversing the input sentence improved seq2seq translation.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The *RNN search* model introduced an attention mechanism to seq2seq for machine translation to solve the bottleneck problem (of the *fixed-size* output vector), allowing the model to process long-distance dependencies more easily.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The name is because it "emulates searching through a source sentence during decoding a translation".
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The relative performances were compared between global (that of *RNN search*) and local (sliding window) attention model architectures for machine translation, finding that mixed attention had higher quality than global attention, while local attention reduced translation time.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In 2016, Google Translate was revamped to Google Neural Machine Translation, which replaced the previous model based on statistical machine translation.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The new model was a seq2seq model where the encoder and the decoder were both 8 layers of bidirectional LSTM.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It took nine months to develop, and it outperformed the statistical approach, which took ten years to develop.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Seq2seq models with attention (including self-attention) still suffered from the same issue with recurrent networks, which is that they are hard to parallelize, which prevented them from being accelerated on GPUs.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In 2016, *decomposable attention* applied a self-attention mechanism to feedforward networks, which are easy to parallelize, and achieved SOTA result in textual entailment with an order of magnitude fewer parameters than LSTMs.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] One of its authors, Jakob Uszkoreit, suspected that attention *without* recurrence would be sufficient for language translation, thus the title "attention is *all* you need".
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] That hypothesis was against conventional wisdom at the time, and even his father Hans Uszkoreit, a well-known computational linguist, was skeptical.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In the same year, self-attention (called *intra-attention or* *intra-sentence attention*) was proposed for LSTMs.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] On 2017-06-12, the original (100M-parameter) encoder–decoder transformer model was published in the "Attention is all you need" paper.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] At the time, the focus of the research was on improving seq2seq for machine translation, by removing its recurrence to process all tokens in parallel, but preserving its dot-product attention mechanism to keep its text processing performance.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This led to the introduction of a multi-head attention model that was easier to parallelize due to the use of independent heads and the lack of recurrence.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Its parallelizability was an important factor to its widespread use in large neural networks.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] As early as spring 2017, even before the "Attention is all you need" preprint was published, one of the co-authors applied the "decoder-only" variation of the architecture to generate fictitious Wikipedia articles.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Transformer architecture is now used alongside many generative models that contribute to the ongoing AI boom.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The "reference implementation" of the original Transformer was written in a TensorFlow library.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In language modelling, ELMo (2018) was a bi-directional LSTM that produces contextualized word embeddings, improving upon the line of research from bag of words and word2vec.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It was followed by BERT (2018), an encoder-only transformer model.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In October 2019, Google started using BERT to process search queries.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model by a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Starting in 2018, the OpenAI GPT series of decoder-only transformers became state of the art in natural language generation.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] At the end of 2022, ChatGPT, a chatbot based on a fine-tuned variant of GPT-3.5, became unexpectedly popular, triggering a boom around large language models.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Transformers have been applied in modalities beyond text.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Four days after the publication of "Attention is All You Need", a multimodal transformer architecture, MultiModel, was published by most authors of that paper.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Other examples include the vision transformer, speech recognition, robotics, and multimodal.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The vision transformer, in turn, stimulated new developments in convolutional neural networks.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The plain transformer architecture had difficulty in converging.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In the original paper, the authors recommended using learning rate warmup.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] That is, the learning rate should linearly scale up from 0 to maximal value for the first part of the training (usually recommended to be 2% of the total number of training steps), before decaying again.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A 2020 paper found that using layer normalization *before* (instead of after) multihead attention and feedforward layers stabilizes training, not requiring learning rate warmup.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This is the "pre-LN Transformer" and is more commonly used, compared to the original "post-LN Transformer".
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Transformers typically are first pretrained by self-supervised learning on a large generic dataset, followed by supervised fine-tuning on a small task-specific dataset.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The pretrain dataset is typically an unlabeled large corpus, such as The Pile.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The T5 transformer report documents a large number of natural language pretraining tasks.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Note that while each of these tasks is trivial or obvious for human native speakers of the language (or languages), they have typically proved challenging for previous generations of machine learning architecture.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In general, there are 3 classes of language modelling tasks: "masked", "autoregressive", and "prefixLM".
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] These classes are independent of a specific modeling architecture such as transformer, but they are often discussed in the context of transformer.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In a masked task, one or more of the tokens is masked out, and the model would produce a probability distribution predicting what the masked-out tokens are based on the context.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The loss function for the task is typically sum of log-perplexities for the masked-out tokens: ${\text{Loss}}=-\sum _{t\in {\text{masked tokens}}}\ln({\text{probability of }}t{\text{ conditional on its context}})$ and the model is trained to minimize this loss function.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The BERT series of models are trained for masked token prediction and another task.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In an autoregressive task, the entire sequence is masked at first, and the model produces a probability distribution for the first token.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Then the first token is revealed and the model predicts the second token, and so on.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The loss function for the task is still typically the same.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The GPT series of models are trained by autoregressive tasks.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In a prefixLM task, the sequence is divided into two parts.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The first part is presented as context, and the model predicts the first token of the second part.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Then that would be revealed, and the model predicts the second token, and so on.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The T5 series of models are trained by prefixLM tasks.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Note that "masked" as in "masked language modelling" is not "masked" as in "masked attention", and "prefixLM" as in "prefix language modeling" is not "prefixLM" as in " prefix language model".
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The following description follows exactly the transformer as described in the original paper.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] There are variants, described in the following section.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] By convention, we write all vectors as row vectors.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] For example, pushing a vector through a linear layer means multiplying it by a weight matrix on the right, as $xW$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] As the transformer architecture natively consists of operations over numbers (matrix multiplications, dot products, activation functions) rather than over text, there must first be a mapping from any input text to some numerical representation.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] First, the input text is treated by a *preprocessor*, which performs both textual transformations and splits the text into coarse-grained segments called *pretokens*.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The latter is referred to as *pretokenization*.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Second, each pretoken is segmented further into *tokens* by a *tokenizer* that expects to only see pretokens output by its preprocessor.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Each token it produces is a string of one or more characters belonging to a finite set of strings called the *vocabulary* V .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Third, because the vocabulary is finite and known beforehand, each token can be assigned an integer identifier, and this mapping is applied to the sequence of tokens to represent any input text as a numerical sequence.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Since this mapping is bijective, the output side can produce a sequence of integer identifiers which can then be turned back into tokens.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] After undoing some of the preprocessing, the result is again legible text.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Training a tokenizer (sometimes referred to as *vocabularization*) means finding a suitable vocabulary V , but also learning how to use it, since any given string s of length $|s|$ has $2^{|s|-1}$ hypothetical segmentations, some of which containing segments that are not in the vocabulary.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The most important hyperparameter during vocabularization is the *vocabulary size* $|V|$ : when it is small, the learned vocabulary generally consists of characters and smaller strings, and words will be segmented into many tokens.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] At larger sizes, it becomes affordable to dedicate tokens to full words, although depending on the preprocessor and tokenizer, it is not necessarily the case that large vocabularies will always use the largest token(s) available to segment a word.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Because tokens are not always full words, they may also be referred to as *subwords* and tokenization algorithms may be referred to as *subword tokenizers*.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This is also to differentiate these systems from traditional terminology used in older information retrieval and natural language processing systems, where "tokenization" was used to denote what is today called "pretokenization" (very crudely: splitting into words).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In tokenizers that produce tokens that are *not* part of the vocabulary, a special token that does belong to the vocabulary is used as a generic stand-in, written as "[UNK]" for "unknown".
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In principle, any string could be hidden by such an [UNK].
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Indeed, in information retrieval, pretokenizers were themselves used as tokenizers (and also called "tokenizers") with a word-level vocabulary that contained an [UNK].
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Commonly used subword tokenization algorithms are byte pair encoding (BPE) and the unigram language model (ULM), which each include a vocabularization algorithm and a dedicated segmentation algorithm.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] There also exist several segmentation algorithms that require no learning and can be applied given a vocabulary (produced by BPE or ULM, for example), like greedily recognising tokens in a pretoken by moving through it left-to-right.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Well-known software implementations of subword tokenizers are Hugging Face's `tokenizers` Python package implemented in Rust, and the `sentencepiece` Python package implemented in C++.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The latter package is named as such because one of its configuration options allows disabling the built-in pretokenizer, hence effectively making entire sentences a pretoken and thus having the tokenizer see entire sentences, rather than individual words.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Each integer token identifier is converted into an embedding vector via a lookup table.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Equivalently stated, it multiplies a one-hot representation of the token identifier by an embedding matrix M .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The dimension of an embedding vector is called *hidden size* or *embedding size* and written as $d_{\text{emb}}$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This size is written as $d_{\text{model}}$ in the original transformer paper.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] An un-embedding layer is almost the reverse of an embedding layer.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Whereas an embedding layer converts a token identifier into a vector, an un-embedding layer converts a vector into a probability distribution over tokens.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The un-embedding layer is a linear-softmax layer: $\mathrm {UnEmbed} (x)=\mathrm {softmax} (xW+b)$ The matrix has shape $(d_{\text{emb}},|V|)$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Some architectures use the transpose of the embedding matrix M as the un-embedding matrix W in order to avoid needing double the amount of embedding-related parameters and to avoid divergence during training.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A positional encoding is a fixed-size vector representation of the relative positions of tokens within a sequence: it provides the transformer model with information about *where* the words are in the input sequence.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This induces a bias towards the order of the input sequence, so that, for example, the input sequence "man bites dog" is processed differently from "dog bites man".
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The positional encoding is defined as a function of type $f:\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , where d is a positive even integer.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Here, N is a free parameter that should be significantly larger than the biggest k that would be input into the positional encoding function.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The main reason for using this positional encoding function is that using it, shifts are linear transformations: $f(t+\Delta t)=\mathrm {diag} (f(\Delta t))f(t)$ where $\Delta t\in \mathbb {R}$ is the distance one wishes to shift.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This allows the transformer to take any encoded position, and find the encoding of the position n-steps-ahead or n-steps-behind, by a matrix multiplication.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] By taking a linear sum, any convolution can also be implemented as linear transformations: $\sum _{j}c_{j}f(t+\Delta t_{j})=\left(\sum _{j}c_{j}\,\mathrm {diag} (f(\Delta t_{j}))\right)f(t)$ for any constants $c_{j}$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This allows the transformer to take any encoded position and find a linear sum of the encoded locations of its neighbors.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This sum of encoded positions, when fed into the attention mechanism, would create attention weights on its neighbors, much like what happens in a convolutional neural network language model.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In typical implementations, all operations are done over the real numbers, not the complex numbers, but since complex multiplication can be implemented as real 2-by-2 matrix multiplication, this is a mere notational difference.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Like earlier seq2seq models, the original transformer model used an **encoder–decoder** architecture.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The encoder consists of encoding layers that process all the input tokens together one layer after another, while the decoder consists of decoding layers that iteratively process the encoder's output and the decoder's output tokens so far.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The purpose of each encoder layer is to create contextualized representations of the tokens, where each representation corresponds to a token that "mixes" information from other input tokens via self-attention mechanism.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Both the encoder and decoder layers have a feed-forward neural network for additional processing of their outputs and contain residual connections and layer normalization steps.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] These feed-forward layers contain most of the parameters in a transformer model.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The feedforward network (FFN) modules in a transformer are 2-layered multilayer perceptrons: $\mathrm {FFN} (x)=\phi (xW^{(1)}+b^{(1)})W^{(2)}+b^{(2)}$ where $W^{(1)}$ and $W^{(2)}$ are weight matrices and $b^{(1)}$ and $b^{(2)}$ are bias vectors, and $\phi$ is its activation function.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The original transformer used ReLU activation.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The number of neurons in the middle layer is called *intermediate size* (GPT), *filter size* (BERT), or *feedforward size* (BERT).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It is typically larger than the embedding size.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] For example, in both GPT-2 series and BERT series, the intermediate size of a model is 4 times its embedding size: $d_{\text{ffn}}=4d_{\text{emb}}$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The attention mechanism used in the transformer architecture are scaled dot-product attention units.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] For each unit, the transformer model learns three weight matrices: the query weights $W^{Q}$ , the key weights $W^{K}$ , and the value weights $W^{V}$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The module takes three sequences, a query sequence, a key sequence, and a value sequence.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The query sequence is a sequence of length $\ell _{\text{seq, query}}$ , and each entry is a vector of dimension $d_{\text{emb, query}}$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Similarly for the key and value sequences.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] For each vector $x_{i,{\text{query}}}$ in the query sequence, it is multiplied by a matrix $W^{Q}$ to produce a query vector $q_{i}=x_{i,{\text{query}}}W^{Q}$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The matrix of all query vectors is the query matrix: $Q=X_{\text{query}}W^{Q}$ Similarly, we construct the key matrix $K=X_{\text{key}}W^{K}$ and the value matrix $V=X_{\text{value}}W^{V}$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It is usually the case that all $W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}$ are square matrices, meaning $d_{\text{emb, query}}=d_{\text{query}}$ , etc.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Attention weights are calculated using the query and key vectors: the attention weight $a_{ij}$ from token i to token j is the dot product between $q_{i}$ and $k_{j}$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The attention weights are divided by the square root of the dimension of the key vectors, ${\sqrt {d_{k}}}$ , which stabilizes gradients during training, and passed through a softmax which normalizes the weights.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The fact that $W^{Q}$ and $W^{K}$ are different matrices allows attention to be non-symmetric: if token i attends to token j (i.e. $q_{i}\cdot k_{j}$ is large), this does not necessarily mean that token j will attend to token i (i.e. $q_{j}\cdot k_{i}$ could be small).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The output of the attention unit for token i is the weighted sum of the value vectors of all tokens, weighted by $a_{ij}$ , the attention from token i to each token.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The attention calculation for all tokens can be expressed as one large matrix calculation using the softmax function, which is useful for training due to computational matrix operation optimizations that quickly compute matrix operations.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The matrices Q , K and V are defined as the matrices where the i th rows are vectors $q_{i}$ , $k_{i}$ , and $v_{i}$ respectively.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] where the softmax is applied over each of the rows of the matrix.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The number of dimensions in a query vector is *query size* $d_{\text{query}}$ and similarly for the *key size* $d_{\text{key}}$ and *value size* $d_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The output dimension of an attention head is its *head dimension* $d_{\text{head}}$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The attention mechanism requires the following three equalities to hold: $\ell _{\text{seq, key}}=\ell _{\text{seq, value}},\;d_{\text{query}}=d_{\text{key}},\;d_{\text{value}}=d_{\text{head}}$ but is otherwise unconstrained.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] If the attention head is used in a self-attention fashion, then $X_{\text{query}}=X_{\text{key}}=X_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] If the attention head is used in a cross-attention fashion, then usually $X_{\text{query}}\neq X_{\text{key}}=X_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It is theoretically possible for all three to be different, but that is rarely the case in practice.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] One set of $\left(W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}\right)$ matrices is called an *attention head*, and each layer in a transformer model has multiple attention heads.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] While each attention head attends to the tokens that are relevant to each token, multiple attention heads allow the model to do this for different definitions of "relevance".
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Specifically, the query and key projection matrices, $W^{Q}$ and $W^{K}$ , which are involved in the attention score computation, defines the "relevance".
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Meanwhile, the value projection matrix $W^{V}$ , in combination with the part of the output projection matrix $W^{O}$ , determines how the attended tokens influence what information is passed to subsequent layers and ultimately the output logits.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In addition, the scope of attention, or the range of token relationships captured by each attention head, can expand as tokens pass through successive layers.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This allows the model to capture more complex and long-range dependencies in deeper layers.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Many transformer attention heads encode relevance relations that are meaningful to humans.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] For example, some attention heads can attend mostly to the next word, while others mainly attend from verbs to their direct objects.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The computations for each attention head can be performed in parallel, which allows for fast processing.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The outputs for the attention layer are concatenated to pass into the feedforward neural network layers.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It is theoretically possible for each attention head to have a different head dimension $d_{\text{head}}$ , but that is rarely the case in practice.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] As an example, in the smallest GPT-2 model, there are only self-attention mechanisms.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The transformer architecture is constructed to calculate output tokens iteratively.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Assuming $t=0$ refers to the calculation of the first output token $i=0$ , for step $t>0$ , the output token $i=0$ shall remain constant.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This ensures properties of the model similar to autoregressive models.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Therefore, at every time step t , the calculation for all outputs i should not have access to tokens at position j for $j>=i$ (as it naturally is the case for time step $t=i$ , when tokens $j>t$ are not yet calculated).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In words, it means that each token can pay attention to itself, and every token before it, but not any after it.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A non-masked attention module can be thought of as a masked attention module where the mask has all entries zero.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] As an example of an uncommon use of mask matrix, the XLNet considers all masks of the form $PM_{\text{causal}}P^{-1}$ , where P is a random permutation matrix.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] An encoder consists of an embedding layer, followed by multiple encoder layers.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Each encoder layer consists of two major components: a self-attention mechanism and a feed-forward layer.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It takes an input as a sequence of input vectors, applies the self-attention mechanism, to produce an intermediate sequence of vectors, then applies the feed-forward layer for each vector individually.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] where ${\text{FFN}}$ stands for "feed-forward network".
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] We can more succinctly write it as ${\text{EncoderLayer}}(H)={\text{FFN}}({\text{MultiheadAttention}}(H,H,H))$ with the implicit convention that the ${\text{FFN}}$ is applied to each row of the matrix individually.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The first encoder layer takes the sequence of input vectors from the embedding layer, producing a sequence of vectors.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This sequence of vectors is processed by the second encoder, and so on.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The output from the final encoder layer is then used by the decoder.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] As the encoder processes the entire input all at once, every token can attend to every other token (all-to-all attention), so there is no need for causal masking.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A decoder consists of an embedding layer, followed by multiple decoder layers, followed by an un-embedding layer.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Each decoder consists of three major components: a causally masked self-attention mechanism, a cross-attention mechanism, and a feed-forward neural network.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The decoder functions in a similar fashion to the encoder, but an additional attention mechanism is inserted which instead draws relevant information from the encodings generated by the encoders.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This mechanism can also be called the *encoder–decoder attention*.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Like the first encoder, the first decoder takes positional information and embeddings of the output sequence as its input, rather than encodings.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The transformer must not use the current or future output to predict an output, so the output sequence must be partially masked to prevent this reverse information flow.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This allows for autoregressive text generation.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] For decoding, all-to-all attention is inappropriate, because a token cannot attend to tokens not yet generated.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Thus, the self-attention module in the decoder is causally masked.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In contrast, the cross-attention mechanism attends to the output vectors of the encoder, which is computed before the decoder starts decoding.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Consequently, there is no need for masking in the cross-attention mechanism.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Schematically, we have: ${\begin{aligned}H'&={\text{MaskedMultiheadAttention}}(H,H,H)\\{\text{DecoderLayer}}(H)&={\text{FFN}}({\text{MultiheadAttention}}(H',H^{E},H^{E}))\end{aligned}}$ where $H^{E}$ is the matrix with rows being the output vectors from the encoder.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The last decoder is followed by a final un-embedding layer to produce the output probabilities over the vocabulary.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Then, one of the tokens is sampled according to the probability, and the decoder can be run again to produce the next token, etc., autoregressively generating output text.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Each encoder layer contains 2 sublayers: the self-attention and the feedforward network.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Each decoder layer contains 3 sublayers: the causally masked self-attention, the cross-attention, and the feedforward network.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The final points of detail are the residual connections and layer normalization, (denoted as "LayerNorm", or "LN" in the following), which while conceptually unnecessary, are necessary for numerical stability and convergence.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The residual connections are introduced to avoid vanishing gradient issues and stabilize the training process.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] They can be expressed by $x\mapsto F(x)+x$ , where F is a given component of the transformer.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Adding the input x can preserve the input information and avoid issues when the gradient of $F(x)$ is close to zero.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Similarly to how the feedforward network modules are applied individually to each vector, the LayerNorm is also applied individually to each vector.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] There are two common conventions in use: the *post-LN* and the *pre-LN* convention.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In the post-LN convention, the output of each sublayer is $\mathrm {LayerNorm} (x+\mathrm {Sublayer} (x))$ where $\mathrm {Sublayer} (x)$ is the function implemented by the sublayer itself.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In the pre-LN convention, the output of each sublayer is $x+\mathrm {Sublayer} (\mathrm {LayerNorm} (x))$ The original 2017 transformer used the post-LN convention.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It was difficult to train and required careful hyperparameter tuning and a "warm-up" in learning rate, where it starts small and gradually increases.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The pre-LN convention, proposed several times in 2018, was found to be easier to train, requiring no warm-up, leading to faster convergence.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The transformer architecture, being modular, allows variations.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Several common variations are described here.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] An "encoder-only" transformer applies the encoder to map an input text into a sequence of vectors that represent the input text.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This is usually used for text embedding and representation learning for downstream applications.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] They are less often used currently, as they were found to be not significantly better than training an encoder–decoder transformer, then taking just the encoder.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] They are also referred to as "all-to-all" or "BERT-like".
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A "decoder-only" transformer is not literally decoder-only, since without an encoder, the cross-attention mechanism has nothing to attend to.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Thus, the decoder layers in a decoder-only transformer is composed of just two sublayers: the causally masked self-attention, and the feedforward network.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This is usually used for text generation and instruction following.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The models in the GPT series and Chinchilla series are decoder-only.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] They are also referred to as "autoregressive" or "causal".
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] An "encoder–decoder" transformer is generally the same as the original transformer, with 2 sublayers per encoder layer and 3 sublayers per decoder layer, etc.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] They might have minor architectural improvements, such as alternative activation functions, changing the location of normalization, etc.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This is also usually used for text generation and instruction following.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The models in the T5 series are encoder–decoder.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A "prefixLM" (prefix language model) is a decoder-only architecture, but with prefix masking, which is different from causal masking.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Specifically, it has mask of the form $M_{\text{prefixLM}}={\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf {0} &-\infty \\\mathbf {0} &M_{\text{causal}}\end{bmatrix}}$ where the first columns correspond to the "prefix", and the subsequent columns correspond to the autoregressively generated text based on the prefix.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] They resemble encoder–decoder models, but has less "sparsity".
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Such models are rarely used, though they are cited as theoretical possibilities and benchmarked comparisons.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p01] For example, in 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model with a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model, as transformer-based decoders did not appear to significantly increase quality unlike the encoder, while the RNN decoder was much faster.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The original transformer uses ReLU activation function.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Other activation functions were developed.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The Llama series and PaLM used SwiGLU; both GPT-1 and BERT used GELU.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Alternative activation functions are often used in combination with Gated Linear Units in the feedforward module.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The normalization used in the transformer can be different from LayerNorm.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] One example is RMSNorm which is used in the Llama series.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Other examples include ScaleNorm and FixNorm.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Transformers may use other positional encoding methods than sinusoidal.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The original transformer paper reported using a learned positional encoding, but finding it not superior to the sinusoidal one.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Later, found that causal masking itself provides enough signal to a transformer decoder that it can learn to implicitly perform absolute positional encoding without the positional encoding module.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Then the RoPE encoding is applied to each pair of coordinates.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The benefit of RoPE is that the dot-product between two vectors depends on their relative location only: ${\text{RoPE}}{\big (}x,m{\big )}^{T}{\text{RoPE}}{\big (}y,n{\big )}={\text{RoPE}}{\big (}x,m+k{\big )}^{T}{\text{RoPE}}{\big (}y,n+k{\big )}$ for any integer k .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] ALiBi (Attention with Linear Biases) is not a *replacement* for the positional encoder on the original transformer.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Instead, it is an *additional* positional encoder that is directly plugged into the attention mechanism.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The idea being that the linear bias matrix is a softened mask.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Just as 0 represent full attention paid, and $-\infty$ represents no attention paid, the linear bias matrix increases attention paid in one direction and decreases attention paid in the other direction.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] ALiBi allows pretraining on short context windows, then fine-tuning on longer context windows.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Since it is directly plugged into the attention mechanism, it can be combined with any positional encoder that is plugged into the "bottom" of the entire network (which is where the sinusoidal encoder on the original transformer, as well as RoPE and many others, are located).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Relative Position Encodings is similar to ALiBi, but more generic: ${\begin{aligned}{\text{Attention}}(Q,K,V)={\text{softmax}}\left({\frac {QK^{\mathrm {T} }}{\sqrt {d_{k}}}}+B\right)V\end{aligned}}$ where B is a Toeplitz matrix, that is, $B_{i,j}=B_{i',j'}$ whenever $i-j=i'-j'$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] This is contrasted with the original sinusoidal positional encoding, which is an "absolute positional encoding".
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The transformer model has been implemented in standard deep learning frameworks such as TensorFlow and PyTorch.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] *Transformers* is a library produced by Hugging Face that supplies transformer-based architectures and pretrained models.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] When an autoregressive transformer is used for inference, such as generating text, the query vector is different at each step, but the already-computed key and value vectors are always the same.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The **KV caching** method saves the computed key and value vectors at each attention block, so that they are not recomputed at each new token.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] PagedAttention applies memory paging to KV caching.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] If a transformer is used with a baked-in prompt, such as ["You are a customer support agent..."], then the key and value vectors can be computed for the prompt, and saved on disk.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The saving in compute is significant when the model is used for many short real-time interactions, such as in online chatbots.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] In general, when a user uses an autoregressive transformer to generate a continuation to a sequence of tokens, the model would first perform a forward-pass on this sequence, whereby the KV caches over this sequence are computed.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Hyperscalers serving large Transformer models may use **disaggregated inference**, wherein prefilling and decoding are performed on separately specialized hardware.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] FlashAttention is an algorithm that implements the transformer attention mechanism efficiently on a GPU.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] It is a communication-avoiding algorithm that performs matrix multiplications in blocks, such that each block fits within the cache of a GPU, and by careful management of the blocks it minimizes data copying between GPU caches (as data movement is slow).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The FlashAttention method is a communication-avoiding algorithm that fuses these operations into a single loop, increasing the arithmetic intensity.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] In practice, FlashAttention operates over multiple queries and keys per loop iteration, in a similar way as blocked matrix multiplication.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] If backpropagation is needed, then the output vectors and the intermediate arrays $[m_{1},\dots ,m_{N}],[\ell _{1},\dots ,\ell _{N}]$ are cached, and during the backward pass, attention matrices are rematerialized from these, making it a form of gradient checkpointing.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] An improved version, FlashAttention-2, was developed to cater to the rising demand for language models capable of handling longer context lengths.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] It offers enhancements in work partitioning and parallelism, enabling it to achieve up to 230 TFLOPs/s on A100 GPUs (FP16/BF16), a 2x speed increase over the original FlashAttention.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Key advancements in FlashAttention-2 include the reduction of non-matmul FLOPs, improved parallelism over the sequence length dimension, better work partitioning between GPU warps, and added support for head dimensions up to 256 and multi-query attention (MQA) and grouped-query attention (GQA).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Benchmarks revealed FlashAttention-2 to be up to 2x faster than FlashAttention and up to 9x faster than a standard attention implementation in PyTorch.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Future developments include optimization for new hardware like H100 GPUs and new data types like FP8.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] FlashAttention-4 focuses on pipelining to increase instruction throughput, and was developed to perform particularly well on Blackwell GPUs.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Multi-Query Attention changes the Multihead Attention mechanism.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] This has a neutral effect on model quality and training speed, but increases inference speed.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] More generally, grouped-query attention (GQA) partitions attention heads into groups, each of which shares the key-value pair.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] MQA is GQA with one group, while standard Multihead Attention is GQA with the maximal number of groups.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Multihead Latent Attention (MLA) is a low-rank approximation to standard MHA.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Specifically, each hidden vector, before entering the attention mechanism, is first projected to two low-dimensional spaces ("latent space"), one for query and one for key-value (KV vector).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] This design minimizes the KV cache, as only the low-dimensional KV vector needs to be cached.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Speculative decoding is a method to accelerate token decoding.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Similarly to speculative execution in CPUs, future tokens are computed quickly, then verified.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] If the quickly computed tokens are incorrect, they are discarded and computed slowly.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The key factor in speculative decoding is that a transformer decoder can verify faster than it can decode, in the following sense.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Suppose we have two transformer models like GPT-3 and GPT-3-small, both with a context window size of 512.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] To generate an entire context window autoregressively with greedy decoding with GPT-3, it must be run for 512 times, each time generating a token $x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{512}$ , taking time $512T_{\text{GPT-3}}$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] However, if we had some educated guess for the values of these tokens, we could verify all of them in parallel, in one run of the model, by checking that each $x_{t}$ is indeed the token with the largest log-likelihood in the t -th output.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] In speculative decoding, a smaller model or some other simple heuristic is used to generate a few speculative tokens that are subsequently verified by the larger model.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] These tokens are then run through the larger GPT-3 in one go.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Suppose that ${\tilde {x}}_{1}$ and ${\tilde {x}}_{2}$ are verified by GPT-3 as what it would have picked, then those are kept, but ${\tilde {x}}_{3}$ is not, so ${\tilde {x}}_{3},{\tilde {x}}_{4}$ are discarded, and GPT-3 is run on those.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] For non-greedy decoding, similar ideas apply, except the speculative tokens are accepted or rejected stochastically, in a way that guarantees the final output distribution is the same as if speculative decoding was not used.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] In Multi-Token Prediction, a single forward pass creates a final embedding vector, which then is un-embedded into a token probability.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] However, that vector can then be further processed by another transformer block to predict the *next* token, and so on for arbitrarily many steps into the future.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] This trades off accuracy for speed, since each new token costs just one more transformer block, rather than the entire stack.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Training transformer-based architectures can be expensive, especially for long inputs.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Many methods have been developed to attempt to address the issue.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] In the image domain, Swin transformer is an efficient architecture that performs attention inside shifting windows.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] In the audio domain, SepTr decouples the attention in time and frequency domains.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] *Long Range Arena* (2020) is a standard benchmark for comparing the behavior of transformer architectures over long inputs.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The standard attention graph is either all-to-all or causal, both of which scales as $O(N^{2})$ where N is the number of tokens in a sequence.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Reformer (2020) reduces the computational load from $O(N^{2})$ to $O(N\ln N)$ by using locality-sensitive hashing and reversible layers.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Sparse attention uses attention graphs that grows slower than $O(N^{2})$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] For example, BigBird (2020) uses random small-world networks which grows as $O(N)$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Ordinary transformers require a memory size that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Attention-free transformers reduce this to a linear dependence while still retaining the advantages of a transformer by linking the key to the value.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Similarly for multiple queries, and for multihead attention.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] This approximation can be computed in linear time, as we can compute the matrix $\varphi (k_{i})v_{i}^{T}$ first, then multiply it with the query.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Transformers can also be used/adapted for modalities (input or output) beyond just text, usually by finding a way to "tokenize" the modality.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Multimodal models can either be trained from scratch, or by finetuning.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] A 2022 study found that transformers pretrained only on natural language can be finetuned on only 0.03% of parameters and become competitive with LSTMs on a variety of logical and visual tasks, demonstrating transfer learning.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The LLaVA was a vision-language model composed of a language model (Vicuna-13B) and a vision model (ViT-L/14), connected by a linear layer.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Vision transformers adapt the transformer to computer vision by breaking down input images as a series of patches, turning them into vectors, and treating them like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Conformer and later Whisper follow the same pattern for speech recognition, first turning the speech signal into a spectrogram, which is then treated like an image, i.e. broken down into a series of patches, turned into vectors and treated like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Perceivers are a variant of transformers designed for multimodality.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] For image generation, notable architectures are DALL-E 1 (2021), Parti (2022), Phenaki (2023), and Muse (2023).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Unlike later models, DALL-E is not a diffusion model.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Instead, it uses a decoder-only transformer that autoregressively generates a text, followed by the token representation of an image, which is then converted by a variational autoencoder to an image.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Parti is an encoder–decoder transformer, where the encoder processes a text prompt, and the decoder generates a token representation of an image.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Muse is an encoder-only transformer that is trained to predict masked image tokens from unmasked image tokens.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] During generation, all input tokens are masked, and the highest-confidence predictions are included for the next iteration, until all tokens are predicted.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] It is a bidirectional masked transformer conditioned on pre-computed text tokens.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The generated tokens are then decoded to a video.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The transformer has had great success in natural language processing (NLP).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] While some language models are capable of generating comprehensible results, machine translation tools remain limited by the complexity of language and emotion, often lacking depth and semantic precision.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Its quality is influenced by linguistic, grammatical, tonal, and cultural differences, making it inadequate to replace real translators fully.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Effective improvement in translation quality requires understanding of target society's customs and historical context, and human intervention and visual cues remain necessary in simultaneous interpretation.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] On the other hand, domain-specific customization, such as for technical documentation or official texts, can yield more stable results, and is commonly employed in multilingual websites and professional databases.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Initial approaches were mostly rule-based or statistical in nature.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] However, these methods have since been superseded by neural machine translation and large language models.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] The origins of machine translation can be traced back to the work of Al-Kindi, a ninth-century Arabic cryptographer who developed techniques for systemic language translation, including cryptanalysis, frequency analysis, and probability and statistics, which are used in modern machine translation.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] The idea of machine translation later appeared in the 17th century.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] In 1629, René Descartes proposed a universal language, with equivalent ideas in different tongues sharing one symbol.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] The idea of using digital computers for translation of natural languages was proposed as early as 1947 by England's A.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Booth and Warren Weaver at Rockefeller Foundation in the same year.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] "The memorandum written by Warren Weaver in 1949 is perhaps the single most influential publication in the earliest days of machine translation." Others followed.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] A demonstration was made in 1954 on the APEXC machine at Birkbeck College (University of London) of a rudimentary translation of English into French.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Several papers on the topic were published at the time, and even articles in popular journals (for example an article by Cleave and Zacharov in the September 1955 issue of *Wireless World*).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] A similar application, also pioneered at Birkbeck College at the time, was reading and composing Braille texts by computer.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Yehoshua Bar-Hillel, began his research at MIT (1951).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] A Georgetown University MT research team, led by Professor Michael Zarechnak, followed (1951) with a public demonstration of its Georgetown-IBM experiment system in 1954.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] MT research programs popped up in Japan and Russia (1955), and the first MT conference was held in London (1956).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Researchers continued to join the field as the Association for Machine Translation and Computational Linguistics was formed in the U.S.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] (1962) and the National Academy of Sciences formed the Automatic Language Processing Advisory Committee (ALPAC) to study MT (1964).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Real progress was much slower, however, and after the ALPAC report (1966), which found that the ten-year-long research had failed to fulfill expectations, funding was greatly reduced.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] According to a 1972 report by the Director of Defense Research and Engineering (DDR&E), the feasibility of large-scale MT was reestablished by the success of the Logos MT system in translating military manuals into Vietnamese during that conflict.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] The French Textile Institute also used MT to translate abstracts from and into French, English, German and Spanish (1970); Brigham Young University started a project to translate Mormon texts by automated translation (1971).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] SYSTRAN, which "pioneered the field under contracts from the U.S. government" in the 1960s, was used by Xerox to translate technical manuals (1978).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Beginning in the late 1980s, as computational power increased and became less expensive, more interest was shown in statistical models for machine translation.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] MT became more popular after the advent of computers.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] SYSTRAN's first implementation system was implemented in 1988 by the online service of the French Postal Service called Minitel.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Various computer based translation companies were also launched, including Trados (1984), which was the first to develop and market Translation Memory technology (1989), though this is not the same as MT.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] The first commercial MT system for Russian / English / German-Ukrainian was developed at Kharkov State University (1991).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] By 1998, "for as little as $29.95" one could "buy a program for translating in one direction between English and a major European language of your choice" to run on a PC.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] MT on the web started with SYSTRAN offering free translation of small texts (1996) and then providing this via AltaVista Babelfish, which racked up 500,000 requests a day (1997).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] The second free translation service on the web was Lernout & Hauspie's GlobaLink.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Franz Josef Och (the future head of Translation Development AT Google) won DARPA's speed MT competition (2003).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] More innovations during this time included MOSES, the open-source statistical MT engine (2007), a text/SMS translation service for mobiles in Japan (2008), and a mobile phone with built-in speech-to-speech translation functionality for English, Japanese and Chinese (2009).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] In 2012, Google announced that Google Translate translates roughly enough text to fill 1 million books in one day.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Before the advent of deep learning methods, statistical methods required a lot of rules accompanied by morphological, syntactic, and semantic annotations.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] The rule-based machine translation approach was used mostly in the creation of dictionaries and grammar programs.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Its biggest downfall was that everything had to be made explicit: orthographical variation and erroneous input must be made part of the source language analyser in order to cope with it, and lexical selection rules must be written for all instances of ambiguity.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Transfer-based machine translation was similar to interlingual machine translation in that it created a translation from an intermediate representation that simulated the meaning of the original sentence.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Unlike interlingual MT, it depended partially on the language pair involved in the translation.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Interlingual machine translation was one instance of rule-based machine-translation approaches.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] In this approach, the source language, i.e. the text to be translated, was transformed into an interlingual language, i.e. a "language neutral" representation that is independent of any language.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] The target language was then generated out of the interlingua.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] The only interlingual machine translation system that was made operational at the commercial level was the KANT system (Nyberg and Mitamura, 1992), which was designed to translate Caterpillar Technical English (CTE) into other languages.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Machine translation used a method based on dictionary entries, which means that the words were translated as they are by a dictionary.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Statistical machine translation tried to generate translations using statistical methods based on bilingual text corpora, such as the Canadian Hansard corpus, the English-French record of the Canadian parliament and EUROPARL, the record of the European Parliament.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Where such corpora were available, good results were achieved translating similar texts, but such corpora were rare for many language pairs.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] The first statistical machine translation software was CANDIDE from IBM.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] In 2005, Google improved its internal translation capabilities by using approximately 200 billion words from United Nations materials to train their system; translation accuracy improved.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] SMT's biggest downfall included it being dependent upon huge amounts of parallel texts, its problems with morphology-rich languages (especially with translating *into* such languages), and its inability to correct singleton errors.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Some work has been done in the utilization of multiparallel corpora, that is a body of text that has been translated into 3 or more languages.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Using these methods, a text that has been translated into 2 or more languages may be utilized in combination to provide a more accurate translation into a third language compared with if just one of those source languages were used alone.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] A deep learning-based approach to MT, neural machine translation has made rapid progress in recent years.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] However, the current consensus is that the so-called human parity achieved is not real, being based wholly on limited domains, language pairs, and certain test benchmarks, i.e., it lacks statistical significance power.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Translations by neural MT tools like DeepL Translator, which is thought to usually deliver the best machine translation results as of 2022, typically still need post-editing by a human.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Instead of training specialized translation models on parallel datasets, one can also directly prompt generative large language models like GPT to translate a text.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] This approach is considered promising, but is still more resource-intensive than specialized translation models.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Studies using human evaluation (e.g. by professional literary translators or human readers) have systematically identified various issues with the latest advanced MT outputs.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Some quality evaluation studies have found that, in several languages, human translations outperform ChatGPT-produced translations in terminological accuracy and clarity of expression.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Common issues include the translation of ambiguous parts whose correct translation requires common sense-like semantic language processing or context.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] There can also be errors in the source texts, missing high-quality training data and the severity of frequency of several types of problems may not get reduced with techniques used to date, requiring some level of human active participation.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Word-sense disambiguation concerns finding a suitable translation when a word can have more than one meaning.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] The problem was first raised in the 1950s by Yehoshua Bar-Hillel.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] He pointed out that without a "universal encyclopedia", a machine would never be able to distinguish between the two meanings of a word.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Today there are numerous approaches designed to overcome this problem.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] They can be approximately divided into "shallow" approaches and "deep" approaches.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Shallow approaches assume no knowledge of the text.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] They simply apply statistical methods to the words surrounding the ambiguous word.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Deep approaches presume a comprehensive knowledge of the word.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] So far, shallow approaches have been more successful.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] The ideal deep approach would require the translation software to do all the research necessary for this kind of disambiguation on its own; but this would require a higher degree of AI than has yet been attained.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] A shallow approach which simply guessed at the sense of the ambiguous English phrase that Piron mentions (based, perhaps, on which kind of prisoner-of-war camp is more often mentioned in a given corpus) would have a reasonable chance of guessing wrong fairly often.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] A shallow approach that involves "ask the user about each ambiguity" would, by Piron's estimate, only automate about 25% of a professional translator's job, leaving the harder 75% still to be done by a human.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] One of the major pitfalls of MT is its inability to translate non-standard language with the same accuracy as standard language.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Heuristic or statistical based MT takes input from various sources in standard form of a language.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Rule-based translation, by nature, does not include common non-standard usages.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] This causes errors in translation from a vernacular source or into colloquial language.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Limitations on translation from casual speech present issues in the use of machine translation in mobile devices.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] In information extraction, named entities, in a narrow sense, refer to concrete or abstract entities in the real world such as people, organizations, companies, and places that have a proper name: George Washington, Chicago, Microsoft.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] It also refers to expressions of time, space and quantity such as 1 July 2011, $500.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] In the sentence "Smith is the president of Fabrionix" both *Smith* and *Fabrionix* are named entities, and can be further qualified via first name or other information; "president" is not, since Smith could have earlier held another position at Fabrionix, e.g.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] The term rigid designator is what defines these usages for analysis in statistical machine translation.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Named entities must first be identified in the text; if not, they may be erroneously translated as common nouns, which would most likely not affect the BLEU rating of the translation but would change the text's human readability.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] They may be omitted from the output translation, which would also have implications for the text's readability and message.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Transliteration includes finding the letters in the target language that most closely correspond to the name in the source language.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] This, however, has been cited as sometimes worsening the quality of translation.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] For "Southern California" the first word should be translated directly, while the second word should be transliterated.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Machines often transliterate both because they treated them as one entity.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Words like these are hard for machine translators, even those with a transliteration component, to process.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Use of a "do-not-translate" list, which has the same end goal – transliteration as opposed to translation – still relies on correct identification of named entities.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] A third approach is a class-based model.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Named entities are replaced with a token to represent their "class"; "Ted" and "Erica" would both be replaced with "person" class token.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Then the statistical distribution and use of person names, in general, can be analyzed instead of looking at the distributions of "Ted" and "Erica" individually, so that the probability of a given name in a specific language will not affect the assigned probability of a translation.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] A study by Stanford on improving this area of translation gives the examples that different probabilities will be assigned to "David is going for a walk" and "Ankit is going for a walk" for English as a target language due to the different number of occurrences for each name in the training data.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] A frustrating outcome of the same study by Stanford (and other attempts to improve named recognition translation) is that many times, a decrease in the BLEU scores for translation will result from the inclusion of methods for named entity translation.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] While no system provides the ideal of fully automatic high-quality machine translation of unrestricted text, many fully automated systems produce reasonable output.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] The quality of machine translation is substantially improved if the domain is restricted and controlled.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] This enables using machine translation as a tool to speed up and simplify translations, as well as producing flawed but useful low-cost or ad-hoc translations.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Machine translation applications have also been released for most mobile devices, including mobile telephones, pocket PCs, PDAs, etc.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] For example, the Google Translate app allows foreigners to quickly translate text in their surrounding via augmented reality using the smartphone camera that overlays the translated text onto the text.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] It can also recognize speech and then translate it.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Despite their inherent limitations, MT programs are used around the world.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Probably the largest institutional user is the European Commission.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] In 2012, with an aim to replace a rule-based MT by newer, statistical-based MT@EC, The European Commission contributed 3.072 million euros (via its ISA programme).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Machine translation has also been used for translating Wikipedia articles and could play a larger role in creating, updating, expanding, and generally improving articles in the future, especially as the MT capabilities may improve.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] There is a "content translation tool" which allows editors to more easily translate articles across several select languages.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] English-language articles are thought to usually be more comprehensive and less biased than their non-translated equivalents in other languages.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] As of 2022, English Wikipedia has over 6.5 million articles while, for example, the German and Swedish Wikipedias each only have over 2.5 million articles, each often far less comprehensive.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Following terrorist attacks in Western countries, including 9-11, the U.S. and its allies have been most interested in developing Arabic machine translation programs, but also in translating Pashto and Dari languages.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Within these languages, the focus is on key phrases and quick communication between military members and civilians through the use of mobile phone apps.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] The Information Processing Technology Office in DARPA hosted programs like TIDES and Babylon translator.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] US Air Force has awarded a $1 million contract to develop a language translation technology.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Lineage W gained popularity in Japan because of its machine translation features allowing players from different countries to communicate.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] The application of this technology in medical settings where human translators are absent is another topic of research, but difficulties arise due to the importance of accurate translations in medical diagnoses.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Researchers caution that the use of machine translation in medicine could risk mistranslations that can be dangerous in critical situations.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Machine translation can make it easier for doctors to communicate with their patients in day-to-day activities, but it is recommended to only use machine translation when there is no other alternative, and that translated medical texts should be reviewed by human translators for accuracy.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Legal language poses a significant challenge to machine translation tools due to its precise nature and atypical use of normal words.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] For this reason, specialized algorithms have been developed for use in legal contexts.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Due to the risk of mistranslations arising from machine translators, researchers recommend that machine translations should be reviewed by human translators for accuracy, and some courts prohibit its use in formal proceedings.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] The use of machine translation in law has raised concerns about translation errors and client confidentiality.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Lawyers who use free translation tools such as Google Translate may accidentally violate client confidentiality by exposing private information to the providers of the translation tools.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] In addition, there have been arguments that consent for a police search that is obtained with machine translation is invalid, with different courts issuing different verdicts over whether or not these arguments are valid.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] The advancements in convolutional neural networks in recent years and in low resource machine translation (when only a very limited amount of data and examples are available for training) enabled machine translation for ancient languages, such as Akkadian and its dialects Babylonian and Assyrian.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] There are many factors that affect how machine translation systems are evaluated.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] These factors include the intended use of the translation, the nature of the machine translation software, and the nature of the translation process.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Different programs may work well for different purposes.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] For example, statistical machine translation (SMT) typically outperforms example-based machine translation (EBMT), but researchers found that when evaluating English to French translation, EBMT performs better.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] The same concept applies for technical documents, which can be more easily translated by SMT because of their formal language.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] In certain applications, however, e.g., product descriptions written in a controlled language, a dictionary-based machine-translation system has produced satisfactory translations that require no human intervention save for quality inspection.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] There are various means for evaluating the output quality of machine translation systems.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] The oldest is the use of human judges to assess a translation's quality.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Even though human evaluation is time-consuming, it is still the most reliable method to compare different systems such as rule-based and statistical systems.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Automated means of evaluation include BLEU, NIST, METEOR, and LEPOR.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Relying exclusively on unedited machine translation ignores the fact that communication in human language is context-embedded and that it takes a person to comprehend the context of the original text with a reasonable degree of probability.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] It is certainly true that even purely human-generated translations are prone to error.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Therefore, to ensure that a machine-generated translation will be useful to a human being and that publishable-quality translation is achieved, such translations must be reviewed and edited by a human.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Such research is a necessary prelude to the pre-editing necessary in order to provide input for machine-translation software such that the output will not be meaningless.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] In addition to disambiguation problems, decreased accuracy can occur due to varying levels of training data for machine translating programs.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Both example-based and statistical machine translation rely on a vast array of real example sentences as a base for translation, and when too many or too few sentences are analyzed accuracy is jeopardized.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Researchers found that when a program is trained on 203,529 sentence pairings, accuracy actually decreases.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] The optimal level of training data seems to be just over 100,000 sentences, possibly because as training data increases, the number of possible sentences increases, making it harder to find an exact translation match.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Flaws in machine translation have been noted for their entertainment value.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] In the early 2000s, options for machine translation between spoken and signed languages were severely limited.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] It was a common belief that deaf individuals could use traditional translators.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] However, stress, intonation, pitch, and timing are conveyed much differently in spoken languages compared to signed languages.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Therefore, a deaf individual may misinterpret or become confused about the meaning of written text that is based on a spoken language.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] (2000), developed a prototype called TEAM (translation from English to ASL by machine) that completed English to American Sign Language (ASL) translations.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] The program would first analyze the syntactic, grammatical, and morphological aspects of the English text.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Following this step, the program accessed a sign synthesizer, which acted as a dictionary for ASL.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] This synthesizer housed the process one must follow to complete ASL signs, as well as the meanings of these signs.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Once the entire text is analyzed and the signs necessary to complete the translation are located in the synthesizer, a computer generated human appeared and would use ASL to sign the English text to the user.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] Only works that are original are subject to copyright protection, so some scholars claim that machine translation results are not entitled to copyright protection because MT does not involve creativity.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/machine-translation] The copyright at issue is for a derivative work; the author of the original work in the original language does not lose his rights when a work is translated: a translator must have permission to publish a translation.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] seq2seq is an approach to machine translation (or more generally, sequence transduction) with roots in information theory, where communication is understood as an encode-transmit-decode process, and machine translation can be studied as a special case of communication.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] This viewpoint was elaborated, for example, in the noisy channel model of machine translation.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] In practice, seq2seq maps an input sequence into a real-numerical vector by using a neural network (the *encoder*), and then maps it back to an output sequence using another neural network (the *decoder*).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] The idea of encoder-decoder sequence transduction had been developed in the early 2010s.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] The papers most commonly cited as the originators that produced seq2seq are two papers from 2014.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] In the seq2seq as proposed by them, both the encoder and the decoder were LSTMs.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] This had the "bottleneck" problem, since the encoding vector has a fixed size, so for long input sequences, information would tend to be lost, as they are difficult to fit into the fixed-length encoding vector.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] The attention mechanism, proposed in 2014, resolved the bottleneck problem.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] They called their model *RNNsearch*, as it "emulates searching through a source sentence during decoding a translation".
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] A problem with seq2seq models at this point was that recurrent neural networks are difficult to parallelize.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] The 2017 publication of Transformers resolved the problem by replacing the encoding RNN with self-attention Transformer blocks ("encoder blocks"), and the decoding RNN with cross-attention causally-masked Transformer blocks ("decoder blocks").
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] One of the papers cited as the originator for seq2seq is (Sutskever et al 2014), published at Google Brain while they were on Google's machine translation project.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] The research allowed Google to overhaul Google Translate into Google Neural Machine Translation in 2016.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] Mikolov had worked on RNNLM (using RNN for language modelling) for his PhD thesis, and is more notable for developing word2vec.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] The encoder is responsible for processing the input sequence and capturing its essential information, which is stored as the hidden state of the network and, in a model with attention mechanism, a context vector.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] The context vector is the weighted sum of the input hidden states and is generated for every time instance in the output sequences.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] The decoder takes the context vector and hidden states from the encoder and generates the final output sequence.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] The decoder operates in an autoregressive manner, producing one element of the output sequence at a time.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] At each step, it considers the previously generated elements, the context vector, and the input sequence information to make predictions for the next element in the output sequence.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] Specifically, in a model with attention mechanism, the context vector and the hidden state are concatenated together to form an attention hidden vector, which is used as an input for the decoder.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] The seq2seq method developed in the early 2010s uses two neural networks: an encoder network converts an input sentence into numerical vectors, and a decoder network converts those vectors to sentences in the target language.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] The Attention mechanism was grafted onto this structure in 2014 and is shown below.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] Later it was refined into the encoder-decoder Transformer architecture of 2017.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] There is a subtle difference between training and prediction.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] During training time, both the input and the output sequences are known.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] During prediction time, only the input sequence is known, and the output sequence must be decoded by the network itself.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] Specifically, consider an input sequence $x_{1:n}$ and output sequence $y_{1:m}$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] The encoder would process the input $x_{1:n}$ step by step.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] After that, the decoder would take the output from the encoder, as well as the <bos> as input, and produce a prediction ${\hat {y}}_{1}$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] Now, the question is: what should be input to the decoder in the next step?
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] A standard method for training is "teacher forcing".
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] In teacher forcing, no matter what is output by the decoder, the next input to the decoder is always the reference.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] That is, even if ${\hat {y}}_{1}\neq y_{1}$ , the next input to the decoder is still $y_{1}$ , and so on.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] During prediction time, the "teacher" $y_{1:m}$ would be unavailable.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] Therefore, the input to the decoder must be ${\hat {y}}_{1}$ , then ${\hat {y}}_{2}$ , and so on.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] It is found that if a model is trained purely by teacher forcing, its performance would degrade during prediction time, since generation based on the model's own output is different from generation based on the teacher's output.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] This is called exposure bias or a train/test distribution shift.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] A 2015 paper recommends that, during training, randomly switch between teacher forcing and no teacher forcing.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] The attention mechanism is an enhancement introduced by Bahdanau et al. in 2014 to address limitations in the basic Seq2Seq architecture where a longer input sequence results in the hidden state output of the encoder becoming irrelevant for the decoder.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] It enables the model to selectively focus on different parts of the input sequence during the decoding process.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] At each decoder step, an alignment model calculates the attention score using the current decoder state and all of the attention hidden vectors as input.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] An alignment model is another neural network model that is trained jointly with the seq2seq model used to calculate how well an input, represented by the hidden state, matches with the previous output, represented by attention hidden state.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] A softmax function is then applied to the attention score to get the attention weight.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] In some models, the encoder states are directly fed into an activation function, removing the need for alignment model.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] An activation function receives one decoder state and one encoder state and returns a scalar value of their relevance.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] Consider the seq2seq language English-to-French translation task.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] To be concrete, let us consider the translation of "the zone of international control <end>", which should translate to "la zone de contrôle international <end>".
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] Here, we use the special <end> token as a control character to delimit the end of input for both the encoder and the decoder.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] An input sequence of text $x_{0},x_{1},\dots$ is processed by a neural network (which can be an LSTM, a Transformer encoder, or some other network) into a sequence of real-valued vectors $h_{0},h_{1},\dots$ , where h stands for "hidden vector".
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] After the encoder has finished processing, the decoder starts operating over the hidden vectors, to produce an output sequence $y_{0},y_{1},\dots$ , autoregressively.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] Here, we use the special <start> token as a control character to delimit the start of input for the decoder.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] The decoding terminates as soon as "<end>" appears in the decoder output.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] As hand-crafting weights defeats the purpose of machine learning, the model must compute the attention weights on its own.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] Taking analogy from the language of database queries, we make the model construct a triple of vectors: key, query, and value.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] The rough idea is that we have a "database" in the form of a list of key-value pairs.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] The decoder sends in a **query**, and obtains a reply in the form of a weighted sum of the **values**, where the weight is proportional to how closely the query resembles each **key**.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] The decoder first processes the "<start>" input partially, to obtain an intermediate vector $h_{0}^{d}$ , the 0th hidden vector of decoder.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] Then, the intermediate vector is transformed by a linear map $W^{Q}$ into a **query** vector $q_{0}=h_{0}^{d}W^{Q}$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] Meanwhile, the hidden vectors outputted by the encoder are transformed by another linear map $W^{K}$ into **key** vectors $k_{0}=h_{0}W^{K},k_{1}=h_{1}W^{K},\dots$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] The linear maps are useful for providing the model with enough freedom to find the best way to represent the data.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] Ideally, the model should have learned to compute the keys and values, such that $q_{0}k_{0}^{T}$ is large, $q_{0}k_{1}^{T}$ is small, and the rest are very small.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] This can be interpreted as saying that the attention weight should be mostly applied to the 0th hidden vector of the encoder, a little to the 1st, and essentially none to the rest.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] In order to make a properly weighted sum, we need to transform this list of dot products into a probability distribution over $0,1,\dots$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] where $v_{0}=h_{0}W^{V},v_{1}=h_{1}W^{V},\dots$ are the **value** vectors, linearly transformed by another matrix to provide the model with freedom to find the best way to represent values.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] Without the matrices $W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}$ , the model would be forced to use the same hidden vector for both key and value, which might not be appropriate, as these two tasks are not the same.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] The particular version described in this section is "decoder cross-attention", as the output context vector is used by the decoder, and the input keys and values come from the encoder, but the query comes from the decoder, thus "cross-attention".
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] Note that the querying vector, $h_{0}^{d}$ , is not necessarily the same as the key-value vector $h_{0}$ .
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] In fact, it is theoretically possible for query, key, and value vectors to all be different, though that is rarely done in practice.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] In 2019, Facebook announced its use in symbolic integration and resolution of differential equations.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] The company claimed that it could solve complex equations more rapidly and with greater accuracy than commercial solutions such as Mathematica, MATLAB and Maple.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] First, the equation is parsed into a tree structure to avoid notational idiosyncrasies.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] An LSTM neural network then applies its standard pattern recognition facilities to process the tree.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] In 2020, Google released Meena, a 2.6 billion parameter seq2seq-based chatbot trained on a 341 GB data set.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] Google claimed that the chatbot has 1.7 times greater model capacity than OpenAI's GPT-2.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] In 2022, Amazon introduced AlexaTM 20B, a moderate-sized (20 billion parameter) seq2seq language model.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] It uses an encoder-decoder to accomplish few-shot learning.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] The encoder outputs a representation of the input that the decoder uses as input to perform a specific task, such as translating the input into another language.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] The model outperforms the much larger GPT-3 in language translation and summarization.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] Training mixes denoising (appropriately inserting missing text in strings) and causal-language-modeling (meaningfully extending an input text).
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] It allows adding features across different languages without massive training workflows.
[src:machine-translation-nlp/seq2seq] AlexaTM 20B achieved state-of-the-art performance in few-shot-learning tasks across all Flores-101 language pairs, outperforming GPT-3 on several tasks.
